A child's immediate social and relational environment can affect their educational success. Family income, education, and structure may affect a child's schooling, according to research. Low-income students are more likely to attend under-resourced schools, lack educational materials and technology, and have fewer extracurricular options. Low-income students may struggle academically and graduate. Parental education affects a child's education. Educational resources and assistance are more likely for children of educated parents, which can improve educational performance. Family structure also affects education. Single-parent families are associated with lower academic attainment and graduation rates. Social capital—networks people's and resources—can also affect educational success. Social capital—access to educational resources and networks—improves academic performance. In conclusion, a child's immediate social and relational environment can affect their educational success. Family income, parental education, family structure, and social capital might affect a child's schooling. 